Of HIV, eight fundamental non-communicable diseases
GENEVA - Non-communicable diseases (NCDs), such as heart disease, stroke, cancer, diabetes, and chronic lung diseases, are responsible for 70% of all deaths.
There is irrefutable evidence that tobacco use, sedentary lifestyle, poor diet, and excessive alcohol consumption increase the chances of prematurely dying from non-communicable diseases.
Yet, despite a broad knowledge of the risks, global obesity is generally not controlled, while tobacco and alcohol consumption continue to rise.
It is in this context that non-communicable disease alliances networks gathered from 9 to 11 December at the second WHO Global Alliance for NCDs Forum in the United Arab Emirates.
In their search for solutions to regulate NCDs, they should draw inspiration from the fight against AIDS.
People living with and affected by HIV continue to lead interventions and their unique form of mobilization has been essential in the progress made.
While the battle is not over, AIDS activists know they can win this battle.
Similarly, a mobilization movement against NCDs can reverse this epidemic.
Yet in 2015, Richard Horton, the editor-in-chief of The Lancet, described the NCD community as being in need of 'a shock to its semi-comatose mind.' He added: 'But who will have the courage to administer it?'
We believe that there are lessons to be learned from AIDS activists.
While the world is focusing on NCD prevention, those who are seeking to control preventable diseases must draw inspiration from the ABC of AIDS activism.
The first letter that the NCD community must take into account is "A", like activism.
Everyone over 40 surely remembers the images of AIDS activists participating in "die-in" during scientific meetings all over the world.
In the United States, AIDS activists took to the streets, even shut down the FDA headquarters for a day in October 1988.
At the global scale, activists have been pressuring governments and pharmaceutical companies to make medications more affordable.
This activism is continuing and should serve as a model for action on non-communicable diseases.
Then, the NCD Community must adopt a more daring approach to budgets - the "B" of the AIDS movement's strategy.
Civic organization and grassroots activism can bring together the initial energies, but the organization and maintenance of a broad coalition require money.
The AIDS movement was clear on this subject from the beginning and has been pressuring to obtain resources to support its awareness and accountability activities effectively.
“C” represents coalitions: the HIV/AIDS movements did not take long to realize that progress only comes with multiple supporters.
The activists established links between people living with HIV and those who were concerned about other issues, such as women's rights, intellectual property rights, nutrition, and housing.
Specialized coalitions and campaigns operate better when they bring together internal and external leaders to public institutions, combining their perspectives and expertise.
The HIV/AIDS movement also understood that a global response to the epidemic is essential to spreading its support.
Thus, “D”, the determining factor of success, consisted of 'drawing attention to the interconnectedness of the challenge.’
For example, lobbying education leaders to keep girls in school longer has contributed to young people having knowledge and power to make intelligent decisions about when and with whom to negotiate protected sexual relationships.
Similarly, links have been made between groups working on poverty, gender equality, and nutrition: all factors that played a major role in the HIV/AIDS crisis.
Non-communicable diseases (NCDs) are no less isolated in their causality and are also subject to a multisectoral approach to prevention.
Commitment - "E" - has been what helped the HIV/AIDS movement gain such great influence.
By strategic borrowing from the disability rights movement, which defended the slogan "Nothing about us without us", advocates for the cause of HIV/AIDS have demanded the representation of affected organizations in the treatment of the disease.
For example, the UNAIDS remains the only UN agency with seats on its Board of Directors reserved for representatives of civil society.
This standard is so deeply ingrained in the fight against AIDS that it would be almost unthinkable for an AIDS meeting to take place without community representation.
The disease prevention movements must also develop convincing narratives and "F" - framing the issue - is essential for the AIDS community to get the support of political leaders.
In particular, access to AIDS treatment has been presented as an issue of economic justice.
Framing the story in this way leads to a significant reduction in the cost of medications, to the point where more than half of people living with HIV in low- and middle-income countries are on treatment.
A formulation just as important of the issue for HIV/AIDS, a highly relevant issue for the NCD movement, is that of responsibility.
The HIV/AIDS community has worked hard to focus more on individuals' life choices, rather than placing the responsibility on the state for providing health care and eliminating legal discrimination.
In the HIV/AIDS debate, gender - the 'G' of our movement - was a significant point.
HIV was initially considered a "gay disease" and gender identity was rooted from the beginning in the DNA of the HIV/AIDS movement.
The gender dimensions of these diseases are no less important: it is enough to look at how alcohol and tobacco are marketed to understand this.
Therefore, gender must become a focal point of NCD prevention efforts.
Finally, 'H' - human rights - are the foundation of the response to AIDS.
Campaigns were launched against discrimination in the workplace, in schools, and in medical facilities.
Strategic litigation has ensured equality before the law.
The AIDS movement refused to hold major conferences in countries with repressive laws against people living with HIV.
The NCD movement could adopt the same tactic, for example, by refusing to meet in countries that are unable to limit unhealthy food advertising to children.
We could continue to list the lessons learned from the fight against HIV/AIDS throughout the alphabet, but it seems appropriate to close on "H", given that human rights provided the response to HIV/AIDS and they should provide the response to non-communicable diseases.
Poverty, exclusion, and social and economic marginalization put people at greater risk of HIV.
The same is true for NCDs.
The first reaction to the HIV/AIDS epidemic was to ask, "Why don't these people make better choices?" The HIV/AIDS movement clearly said that this question is not the right one.
Today, with 70% of the planet at risk of premature death due to preventable diseases, "those people" represent a large number of us.
The NCD and AIDS communities can learn from each other.
We are a stronger movement when we unite our forces.
The views expressed here do not necessarily reflect those of UNAIDS.
